content.description:
Yet another great moderate!

 Left of the rib, through the alcove, up to a crack, and exit.
content.location: Near the center of the main face.

content.description:
The main slot is lined with the hollowed out remains of a tree (in 2020).  Fun climbing with a unique, wooden crux.

 Once past the crux, there are several exits at the top.
content.location: The rightmost route in the main part of the west face.  The wood-lined crack should make this easy to identify.

content.description: A chimney with a roof.  Looks more ominous than it is. (60 year old?) piton tucked up under the roof - don't clip it!
content.location: The gaping chimney just to the right of the main face.

content.description: The wide chimney on the north face.
content.protection: You could use some big gear.
content.location: Up and around to the left of the main face.

content.description:
Great hands, but slick feet!  A one-move wonder.

 A couple of different starts will get you up to the smooth face with the incipient crack.  Mantle up to the left of the nose above.
Start to the left of the skinny rib.  Pull onto the rib and exit up the crack above.
content.protection: From micro nuts and/or cams to an oversized cam.  You'll want small gear at the bottom, and you could use a big piece at the bulge.
content.location: Immediately left of Squirrel's Nest, in the center of the face.

content.description: Use the face and crack to start.  At the level of the 60-year-old piton, traverse out to the right.  Finish up.
content.protection: Well, there's this old rusty piton ....
content.location: In the middle section of the north face.

content.description:
A devious line - it can be hard to spot the next good hold.

 Begin in the dihedral just left of the main face.  Climb to a horizontal break and traverse right into a shallow dihedral.  Continue straight up.
content.protection: Not a lot in the crux
content.location: Leftmost route on the main face.

content.description: Forgotten for decades at a time, this buttress is host to some amazingly aesthetic moderates.
